acp{SNR}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Rather than recording noise in a range of conditions directly, it is more
 convenient to have separate speech and noise and to model the speech with
 noise signal.
 Thus, the effects of babble are often modelled rather than directly recorded.
 This type of babble can be classed as synthetic babble, and may or may
 not accurately represent real babble 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krishnamurthy2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common method of creating synthetic babble is to use a number of
 speech recordings, adding them together to form babble.
 This presents a number of issues.
 Firstly, real conversations are not simply a number of voices speaking
 simultaneously.
 Rather, conversations are dynamic, where there is generally one speaker
 but occasionally more or none 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krishnamurthy2009"

\end_inset

.
 Secondly, synthetic babble generally does not take into effect environmental
 effects, such as reverberation, generally present alongside babble 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Krishnamurthy2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

